Here's a test that currently fails in my repo:

```
            asyncTest("require() a script, execute callback post-load via wait()", function(){
                   expect(2);
                   basket
                       .require("jquery-1.7.1.min.js")
                       .wait(function(){
                            ok(true, "callback invoked");
                            ok(
                                localStorage.getItem("basket-jquery-1.7.1.min.js"),
                                "waited correctly"
                            );
                            start();
                       });
            });
```

Wrapping the asserts in a `setTimeout` passes the test, indicating that `.wait()` doesn't actually wait, it's just been quick so we haven't noticed. :)

Good work spotting that, @peol! Depending on what our definition for .wait()'s behaviour is, it should either wait until all of the dependencies in the chain above it have resolved:

```
basket.require('jquery.js').require('underscore.js').wait( callback );
//where jquery and underscore should both be resolved before the callback is executed
```

 or until the .require() its been attached to has completed loading:

```
basket.require('jquery.js').require('underscore.js').wait( callback );
//callback executed when underscore.js has completed, but we dont care about the state of jquery
```

LabJS appears to opt for the former http://labjs.com/documentation.php#wait. Do we want to go with the same?

Yes, that's at least what I had in mind when seeing a `wait()` function. If you want wait for individuals, we could perhaps go for something like this:

```
basket
  .require('jquery.js')
  .require('underscore.js')
  .wait({
    'jquery.js': function() {},
    'underscore.js': function() {}
  },
  // second param to .wait(), if first is an object, will invoke when all has been loaded
  function() {});
```

Without specific-callback object:

```
basket
  .require('jquery.js')
  .require('underscore.js')
  .wait(function() {
    // invoked when all has been loaded
  });
```

or simply do:

```
basket
  .require("foo.bar.js", function() {})
  .require("bar.foo.js", function() {})
  .wait(function(){});
```

I think the former is easier though.

Agreed. Also, this should probably work...:

